<taxonomicName id="4C5A5892FFABFFCC7FBDFABDF75EDC57" box="[470,597,1343,1366]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="limoncocha">limoncocha</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 53, male head, v.v.; 54, male mesofurcasternal plate; 55, female abdominal sternum VIII, l.v.; 56, same, v.v.; 57, male genitalia, v.v.; 58, same, l.v.; 59, detail of apex of penes.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BE52311FFABFFCC7EADFA1DF14FDF75" blockId="18.[151,1437,1439,2025]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Female imago. Length (mm): body (shrunken abdomen), 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7D02FA1DF694DCB8" box="[873,927,1439,1465]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="10.5">10.5</number>
; fore wing, 16.0; hind wing, 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7A9FFA1DF017DCB8" box="[1268,1308,1439,1465]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="6.9">6.9</number>
; cerci, 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7B1BFA1DF093DCB8" box="[1392,1432,1439,1465]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="4.5">4.5</number>
. As in male, exceptions follow. Antennae with scape and pedicel brownish black. Thorax shaded more markedly with brownish gray. Legs yellowish white shaded brownish, turning lighter towards apex. Wings as male except usual sexual dimorphism (thicker veins). Abdomen yellowish strongly shaded brownish gray. Sternum VIII shaded strongly with black, lighter anteriorly; sockets blackish, relatively short and with more or less transverse opening (
<figureCitation id="13613F94FFABFFCC7FBDF9D8F727DF75" box="[470,556,1626,1652]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 ‚Äì 13" captionStartId="10.[151,270,1119,1143]" captionTargetBox="[169,1402,195,1092]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,175,1095]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 10 ‚Äì 13. Tortopus bellus: 10, male genitalia, v. v.; 11, details of apex of penes; 12, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 13, sockets on female abdominal sternum VIII." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195433/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7C66F9D8F727DF75" box="[525,556,1626,1652]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
), anterior depressed area paler. Cerci whitish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE52311FFABFFCD7EADF9FDF780D9D6" blockId="18.[151,1437,1439,2025]" lastBlockId="19.[151,1435,152,215]" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Discussion and diagnosis. A short description of the male is given to complete the original description by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFCB5EE0FFABFFCC7EFCF926F72FDFBF" author="Lugo-Ortiz" box="[151,548,1700,1726]" pageId="18" pageNumber="34" refString="Lugo-Ortiz, C. R. &amp; McCafferty W. P. (1996) Central American Tortopus (Ephemeroptera: Polymitarcyidae): a unique new species and new country records. Entomological News, 107, 23 - 27." type="journal article" year="1996">
Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty (
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7FB6F926F710DFBF" box="[477,539,1700,1726]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1996.0">1996</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
with some new characters for the group. The female adult is described for the first time. 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5892FFABFFCC7F2AF948F70ADFE2" box="[321,513,1738,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Tortopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellus">
<emphasis id="B92EFF03FFABFFCC7F2AF948F70ADFE2" box="[321,513,1738,1763]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Tortopus bellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other species in the genus by: 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7ADFF948F1CADFE5" box="[1204,1217,1738,1764]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1.0">1</number>
) fore wing length 
<quantity id="4CA28EF4FFABFFCC7EFCF96DF449DE08" box="[151,322,1775,1801]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.17" metricValueMax="1.29" metricValueMin="1.05" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="11.7" valueMax="12.9" valueMin="10.5">10.5‚Äì12.9 mm</quantity>
(female 16.0 mm); 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7C44F96DF735DE08" box="[559,574,1775,1801]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2.0">2</number>
) parastyli very short and pointed (
<figureCitation id="13613F94FFABFFCC7DBEF96DF151DE08" box="[981,1114,1775,1801]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 ‚Äì 13" captionStartId="10.[151,270,1119,1143]" captionTargetBox="[169,1402,195,1092]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,175,1095]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 10 ‚Äì 13. Tortopus bellus: 10, male genitalia, v. v.; 11, details of apex of penes; 12, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 13, sockets on female abdominal sternum VIII." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195433/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 10, 12</figureCitation>
); 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7A1AF96DF18BDE08" box="[1137,1152,1775,1801]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="3.0">3</number>
) ventral knob relatively small (
<figureCitation id="13613F94FFABFFCC7E8CF896F434DE2F" box="[231,319,1812,1838]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 ‚Äì 13" captionStartId="10.[151,270,1119,1143]" captionTargetBox="[169,1402,195,1092]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,175,1095]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 10 ‚Äì 13. Tortopus bellus: 10, male genitalia, v. v.; 11, details of apex of penes; 12, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 13, sockets on female abdominal sternum VIII." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195433/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7F74F896F434DE2F" box="[287,319,1812,1838]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
); 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7F3DF896F46DDE2F" box="[342,358,1812,1838]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="4.0">4</number>
) penes relatively wide (
<figureCitation id="13613F94FFABFFCC7CEAF896F7D2DE2F" box="[641,729,1812,1838]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 ‚Äì 13" captionStartId="10.[151,270,1119,1143]" captionTargetBox="[169,1402,195,1092]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,175,1095]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 10 ‚Äì 13. Tortopus bellus: 10, male genitalia, v. v.; 11, details of apex of penes; 12, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 13, sockets on female abdominal sternum VIII." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195433/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7CD2F896F7D2DE2F" box="[697,729,1812,1838]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
); 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7C9BF896F7F4DE2F" box="[752,767,1812,1838]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="5.0">5</number>
) female with sockets on s. VIII relatively wide and with transverse opening (
<figureCitation id="13613F94FFABFFCC7FE8F8B8F4D1DE55" box="[387,474,1850,1876]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 ‚Äì 13" captionStartId="10.[151,270,1119,1143]" captionTargetBox="[169,1402,195,1092]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,175,1095]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 10 ‚Äì 13. Tortopus bellus: 10, male genitalia, v. v.; 11, details of apex of penes; 12, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 13, sockets on female abdominal sternum VIII." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195433/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7FD1F8B8F4D1DE55" box="[442,474,1850,1876]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
); and 
<number id="3D923136FFABFFCC7C49F8B8F73ADE55" box="[546,561,1850,1876]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="6.0">6</number>
) a relatively dark species, dorsum of head almost entirely shaded black. Male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5892FFABFFCC7F07F8DDF728DE79" box="[364,547,1887,1912]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Tortopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellus">
<emphasis id="B92EFF03FFABFFCC7F07F8DDF728DE79" box="[364,547,1887,1912]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Tortopus bellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5892FFABFFCC7C94F8DDF6CADE79" box="[767,961,1887,1912]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Tortopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="harrisi">
<emphasis id="B92EFF03FFABFFCC7C94F8DDF6CADE79" box="[767,961,1887,1912]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Tortopus harrisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5892FFABFFCC7A75F8DDF188DE79" box="[1054,1155,1887,1912]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Tortopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellus">
<emphasis id="B92EFF03FFABFFCC7A75F8DDF188DE79" box="[1054,1155,1887,1912]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">T. bellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the knob at the base of forceps is reduced, pedestals have a widely rounded posteromedial corner (opposite to parastylus), forceps are completely shaded black and penes are much wider. Further differences between both species include: a darker coloration in 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5892FFABFFCC7FE4F84DF4FDDEE9" box="[399,502,1999,2024]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Tortopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellus">
<emphasis id="B92EFF03FFABFFCC7FE4F84DF4FDDEE9" box="[399,502,1999,2024]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">T. bellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with abdominal terga and sterna shaded strongly with brownish gray (sterna unmarked in 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5892FFAAFFCD7F52FF1AF4A0D9B0" box="[313,427,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Tortopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="harrisi">
<emphasis id="B92EFF03FFAAFFCD7F52FF1AF4A0D9B0" box="[313,427,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">T. harrisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and wing venation without short marginal intercalaries in MA and R regions (
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5892FFAAFFCD7BEDFF1AF5ECD9D7" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Tortopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="harrisi">
<emphasis id="B92EFF03FFAAFFCD7BEDFF1AF5ECD9D7" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">T. harrisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus id="54E19DB3FFAAFFCD7E86FF3FF45FD9D6" box="[237,340,189,215]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">holotype</typeStatus>
presents 
<number id="3D923136FFAAFFCD7FA8FF3FF4DAD9D6" box="[451,465,189,215]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="3.0">3</number>
of these veins).
</paragraph>
